{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_leadville_ver01/data/sn90051167/00340586086/1921010401/1447.xml":{"full_text":"THE STATE HERALD\nVOLUME XXXV.\nSEARCH IS BEING MADE\nFOR DE VALERA, WHO\nRETURNS TO IRELAND\n(Special by United PreM.)\nNew York, Dec. 31\u2014De Valera, the\npresident of the Irish republic, has re\nturned to Ireland, aa announced by\nhie secretary, Harry Boland.\n(The Irish president spent more than\na year in the United States in behalf\nof the Sinn Fein. Boland refuses to\nsay when and where De Valera land\ned. Presumably, he returned to enter\ninto peace negotiations. English offi\ncials said he would be arrested on\nreturn.\nDe Valera declared that it Mac-\nSwiney died on his hunger strike, ho\nwould return to Ireland and go on a\nhunger strike. He probably will be 1\nleader of the Sinn Fein.\nDublin. Jan. 3 \u2014Ooverr-v r.tj\nare in a nation-wl*\u2019*' fir De\nValera, who in z \"w. 11 have land\ned here fro i. He is liable\nto arr i f j .jo has been a fugitive\nsince I; j t i:*o from an English;\njail.\nBritish afficilas have not announced\nthe governments policy against De\nValera. There is a wide spread be-1\nlief that ho was allowed to enter Ire-\nland to use his influence to bring;\nabout peace. A fresh Sinn Fein out- j\nburst is feared, however.\n,k London, Jan. 3 \u2014Reprisals against\nSinn Feincrs were made official by i\ntin? military. Hereafter, those who\nfall to prevent damage to government\nproperty are liable to punishment- To\nthose who do damage the penalty will\nbe inflicted either against their per\nsons or property.\nThe announu vuxt 1 thrown prop\nerty owners of Ireland Into conster\nnation. Newspapers are divided on\nthe announcement; some claim U is\nthe right policy, while osiers say the\nproperty owners might not be aware\nof the Intended damage .and should\nnot ho punished, calling It a drastic\nstep.\nD'Annunzio's Soldiers\nEvacuating Fiume\n(Special liy United Proas.)\nRome, Jan. 3 D'Annunzio's defeat\ned rcldlers will