be cut\ndown considerably.\nFederal reserve board experts de\nclare that the most diffic i*t utajj of\ntho readjustment .rrlr.i h.:. passed.\nTwo Prominent Men\nKilled and Payroll of\nTheir Plant Stolen\n(Special by United Press.)\nCleveland, 0.. Dec- 31\u2014W. C. Sly.\npresident, and George Farmer, vice\npresident of the W. W. Sly Manu\nfacturing Company were shot am}\nj killed by five automobile bandits on\nI tho streets at noon today.\nThe bandits escaped with the pay#\nj roll of $4,500.\nj The bandits crashed into tho Sly\nj automobile, and In the argument over\nthe blame for the wreck, the bandits\ni deliberately killed both men. They\nthou seized the payroll and sped away\n;in nu accomplice s machine which\nI drove up.\nCalifornia University\nDefeats Ohio 28 to 0\n(Special by United Pr-*s*\u00ab.)\nPusudenu, Calif., Jan. I\u2014Four hours\nl>efore the game between Ohio State\nand California University, the field\nwas filled with of persons\nto see tho football classic which de\ncided the championship of the LuHt\nand West.\nIt was u perfect day for football.\nTho coaches of both teams refused\nto make predictions. Californians ap\nparently were not worried, hut Ohio\nans were taking everythin seriously\nOfficial estimates put tho attend\nsnee at 42.000. wifi- thousands unable\nto gain admittance.\nCalifornia scored in the first period\n1 after recovering the bull on u fumbl\nun tho Buckeye thirty yard lino, a\n1 forward pass gained fifteen yards,\nI und un end run und two lino bucks\nputting the ball ucross the line.\nA fifty yard push by Muller 111 tho\nt eeond period wns responsible for u\n\u2022eond touchdown for California\nTho game ended 28 to 0 in favor\nof California.\nMining Bill Signed\nby President Wilson\n(Special by United Pr*an.)\nWashington. Dec. 31 President\nWilson signed tho Houdoraon mining\nhill, granting temporary relief to inln\nn* who have been unable to do th**\nrequired amount of work on their\nTuims during tho pust year.\nTho bill, which extends until July l\nthe Lime in which minors may do\nf 100 worth of work upon their claims\nfor 1929, was the occasion of Senator\n'\u2022burst's visit tf) the White llous\u00bb\nVcduosdoy to speed up the action of\nI the bill.\nHad no uction been taken, thou- 1\nnnds of claims throughout tho West\nwould have been Ruble to occupancy\nby claim Jumpers, who re locato the\n\u2018claims because the original owner\nhad failed to do tho required work\nupon tilt* claim.\nBandit Wounds Agent\nof Express Company\n(H i#* i'li)l hy United Press.)\nSpencer. In.. Jun. 3- Charles J\nPhillips, express compuny agent, was\nfatally wounded by a bandit who os\naped with several hundred dollars\nthis morning. Peases arc searching\nfor tip* bandit.\nPhillips bus n wife and four chll-\nI dren.\nDirector of Bureau\nof Mines Resigns\n(Hpcclnl by United Press I\nWashington. Jan. 3 Dr. K. G. Colt\n1 reil, director of bureuu of mines, re\nsigned to accept the chairmanship of\ntin* division of chemistry oii the tm\ni tloiiui research council 11. Foster\ni Haiti of California was recommended\n\u2022by Cottrell ns Ills successor.\nA SEMI-WEEKLY PUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY AND FRIDAY\nHOLYOKE, PHILLIPS COUNTY, COLORADO, TUEBDAY, JANUARY 4, 1921\n(Special by United Tress.)\ni and that the economic situation Is\nsounder than it wus u year ago. They\nwill attempt to hold government ap\ni propriatlons to three billion dollars.\ni\ni Washington, Jan. 3\u2014Government\ni officials of the treasury, agricultural\nt und labor departments declare that\nprosperity is bound to return in the\nspring, und that it will mean tho end\nf of unemployment and strikes preval\nout throughout the country; and gen-\nThe Holyoke Business Mans\nResolutions for Year of 1921\nFirst I hereby resolve, that duffing tho coming year, I will\nA lay nalde nil petty jealousies and strive to work with, instead\nt\n4> oi against other business men of the town.\ni\nT\nSecond- I believe in Holyoke njid her full.re, and will on-\ndea